Below is an HTML file containing embedded CSS and JavaScript that implements a simple version of a blocks world system similar to SHRDLU. This code creates a canvas where users can input commands to manipulate blocks. The basic commands implemented are "stack", "unstack", and "move".

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Blocks World Simulator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        #canvas {
            border: 1px solid #000;
            margin: 20px auto;
            display: block;
        }
        #input {
            margin-top: 10px;
            padding: 10px;
            width: 400px;
        }
        #submit {
            padding: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Blocks World Simulator</h1>
<canvas id="canvas" width="500" height="400"></canvas>
<input type="text" id="input" placeholder="Enter a command (e.g., 'stack A on B')" />
<button id="submit">Submit</button>
<p id="output"></p>

<script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
    const output = document.getElementById('output');

    const blocks = {
        A: { x: 50, y: 300, height: 20 },
        B: { x: 150, y: 300, height: 20 },
        C: { x: 250, y: 300, height: 20 },
    };

    function drawBlock(name, x, y) {
        ctx.fillStyle = 'skyblue';
        ctx.fillRect(x, y - blocks[name].height, 50, blocks[name].height);
        ctx.strokeStyle = 'black';
        ctx.strokeRect(x, y - blocks[name].height, 50, blocks[name].height);
    }

    function clearCanvas() {
        ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
    }

    function drawBlocks() {
        clearCanvas();
        for (let block in blocks) {
            drawBlock(block, blocks[block].x, blocks[block].y);
        }
    }

    function handleCommand(command) {
        const parts = command.split(' ');
        if (parts[0] === 'stack' && parts.length === 4) {
            const block1 = parts[1];
            const block2 = parts[3];

            if (blocks[block1] && blocks[block2]) {
                blocks[block1].y = blocks[block2].y - blocks[block1].height;
                output.innerText = `Staked ${block1} on ${block2}`;
            } else {
                output.innerText = 'Invalid blocks';
            }
        } else if (parts[0] === 'unstack' && parts.length === 3) {
            const block1 = parts[1];
            const block2 = parts[2];

            if (blocks[block1]) {
                blocks[block1].y = 300; // Put it back to ground level for simplicity
                output.innerText = `Unstacked ${block1} from ${block2}`;
            } else {
                output.innerText = 'Invalid block';
            }
        } else if (parts[0] === 'move' && parts.length === 4) {
            const block1 = parts[1];
            const block2 = parts[3];

            if (blocks[block1] && blocks[block2]) {
                blocks[block1].x = blocks[block2].x;
                output.innerText = `Moved ${block1} to ${block2}`;
            } else {
                output.innerText = 'Invalid blocks';
            }
        } else {
            output.innerText = 'Unknown command';
        }
        drawBlocks();
    }

    document.getElementById('submit').onclick = function() {
        const command = document.getElementById('input').value.trim();
        handleCommand(command);
        document.getElementById('input').value = '';
    };

    // Initial drawing
    drawBlocks();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use
1. Copy the entire code and paste it into a new HTML file (e.g., `blocks_world.html`).
2. Open this file in a web browser.
3. Use the input box to type commands like:
   - `stack A on B`
   - `unstack A from B`
   - `move A to B`
4. Press the "Submit" button to execute the command.
5. The canvas will display the blocks according to your commands.

### Features
- You can stack block A on B, unstack it, and move blocks around.
- The drawing on the canvas is updated after each command to reflect the current state of the blocks.
- Basic validation for the commands is included, with error messages displayed for invalid commands. 

Feel free to expand the functionality as needed!

Certainly! Below is an HTML file that uses A-Frame to create a 3D Blocks World visualization. This code allows you to issue commands to manipulate blocks in a 3D space using simple commands similar to SHRDLU. The blocks can be stacked, unstacked, and moved around.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>3D Blocks World Simulator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        #commandInput {
            position: absolute;
            top: 20px;
            left: 20px;
            z-index: 10;
            background: white;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div id="commandInput">
    <input type="text" id="input" placeholder="Enter command (e.g., 'stack A on B')" />
    <button id="submit">Submit</button>
    <p id="output"></p>
</div>

<!-- A-Frame Scene -->
<a-scene embedded>
    <a-assets>
        <!-- You can add textures or models here -->
    </a-assets>

    <a-entity camera position="0 2 5" look-controls></a-entity>

    <a-entity id="A" geometry="primitive: box; width: 1; height: 0.2; depth: 1" material="color: #4CC3D2" position="0 0.1 0"></a-entity>
    <a-entity id="B" geometry="primitive: box; width: 1; height: 0.2; depth: 1" material="color: #EF2D5E" position="2 0.1 0"></a-entity>
    <a-entity id="C" geometry="primitive: box; width: 1; height: 0.2; depth: 1" material="color: #FFC65D" position="4 0.1 0"></a-entity>
</a-scene>

<script>
    const output = document.getElementById('output');
    const blocks = {
        A: { el: document.getElementById('A'), y: 0.1 },
        B: { el: document.getElementById('B'), y: 0.1 },
        C: { el: document.getElementById('C'), y: 0.1 },
    };

    function updateBlockHeight(blockName) {
        const block = blocks[blockName];
        block.el.setAttribute('position', `0 ${block.y} 0`);
    }

    function handleCommand(command) {
        const parts = command.split(' ');
        if (parts[0] === 'stack' && parts.length === 4) {
            const block1 = parts[1];
            const block2 = parts[3];

            if (blocks[block1] && blocks[block2]) {
                blocks[block1].y = blocks[block2].y + 0.2; // Stack on top
                output.innerText = `Stacked ${block1} on ${block2}`;
                updateBlockHeight(block1);
            } else {
                output.innerText = 'Invalid blocks';
            }
        } else if (parts[0] === 'unstack' && parts.length === 3) {
            const block1 = parts[1];
            const block2 = parts[2];

            if (blocks[block1]) {
                blocks[block1].y = 0.1; // Put it back to ground level
                output.innerText = `Unstacked ${block1} from ${block2}`;
                updateBlockHeight(block1);
            } else {
                output.innerText = 'Invalid block';
            }
        } else if (parts[0] === 'move' && parts.length === 4) {
            const block1 = parts[1];
            const block2 = parts[3];

            if (blocks[block1] && blocks[block2]) {
                blocks[block1].el.setAttribute('position', `${blocks[block2].el.getAttribute('position').x} ${blocks[block1].y} ${blocks[block2].el.getAttribute('position').z}`);
                output.innerText = `Moved ${block1} to ${block2}`;
            } else {
                output.innerText = 'Invalid blocks';
            }
        } else {
            output.innerText = 'Unknown command';
        }
    }

    document.getElementById('submit').onclick = function() {
        const command = document.getElementById('input').value.trim();
        handleCommand(command);
        document.getElementById('input').value = '';
    };
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the entire code and paste it into a new HTML file (e.g., `3d_blocks_world.html`).
2. Open this file in a web browser that supports WebGL (most modern browsers do).
3. To interact with the blocks, you can type commands in the input box and try commands such as:
   - `stack A on B`
   - `unstack A from B`
   - `move A to B`
4. Press the "Submit" button to execute the command.
5. The 3D visualization will update to reflect the state of the blocks based on your commands.

### Features:
- The blocks are represented as colored boxes in a 3D space.
- Basic commands for stacking, unstaking, and moving blocks are implemented.
- Simple user interface for inputting commands.
- The camera can be moved for a better view of the blocks.

Feel free to customize the block colors, sizes, and add more commands or functionalities as you see fit!
